Â @bigliambigÂ  The mummy was one of the best rides in universal. Lots of great air time and the theming is on point. It is definitely one of the mildest coasters at universal. Dueling dragons was probably one of the smoothest rides until they redid hulk. Hulk is ridiculously smooth now and I highly recommend it although the line is always stupidly long. Pro tips: Always head to the back of the park first and do the popular rides at lunchtime when everyone is eating. Also hit the back of the park again near closing for almost no wait since everyone will be working their way back to the front of the park to leave. And if you don't like bumpy rides never sit in the very back, you may think it's the calmest part but if you know physics you know that you'll get the most side to side action; however, you 100% get the greatest airtime in the back since the front has already accelerated in the drop so you essentially get whipped through the end of the lift into the drop. If you want even more airtime scoot your butt forward on the seat and press your back to the seat, that way it looks like your sitting all the way back but you are actually leaving a gap after the strap you in so you can literally lift up out of your seat on airtime hills and drops. And for people scared of going upside down, as I was when I first started riding coasters, look forward because it's harder to tell you're upside down since all you see is track in front of you, plus the rolls are over in about a second anyways.

It's actually better to sit in the front. You get the most whiplash and freefall in the back. (Arenaline junkies know this, and for that reason love it in the back.) People who don't like a lot of freefall, however, make the mistake of sitting back when they're likely better off at the front. I'm one of those who like rides for the speed, not so much the height and freefall. I like the front because I'd rather see where I'm going and how far I'm from the ground. I also keep my eyes open, because falls seem longer and worse with my eyes shut. And, for some reason, letting my hands out at the falls feels better than clamming up and gripping the safety bars. Funny, I find that everything to make a ride more enjoyable than scary completely goes against what scared people would think to do. So sit in the front, loosen up, relax, and open your eyes. :) I wish I could tell all this to poor Kevin, and he would've had a better time.

Stocking AnarchyÂ Um Kingda Ka opened in 2005 and El Toro opened in 2006 which means Kingda Ka is older than El Toro. Â Just sayin'. Â And I don't feel like I'm going to die on El Toro or any coaster but I prefer El Toro because it has amazing airtime and those 90 degree banked turns are super fun. Â And also, lap bars are super safe. Â In fact, Top Thrill Dragster, a coaster at Cedar Point a lot like Kingda Ka just has lap bars. Â And a lot of large coasters have lap bars like El Toro, Millennium Force, Fury 325, Bizarro and countless others. Â Also, ALL roller coaster supports sway. Â You need that give or else the tension from the trains' force would be too great and deteriorate the structure. Â A roller coaster without swaying supports would not last long. Sorry, made a couple of mistakes in my last post. The park is called "Fuji Q Highland". I went there like 7 years ago so... And Dodompa is or was the record holder for fastest acceleration. The start is extremely fast. There are some videos of the coasters on Youtube. My height information was correct but the actual height from the ground at the highest point is 79m. The bottom is 9m off the ground, so the first drop is 70m.

For you guys talking about the biggest roller coasters etc. You should check out Fujiyama Park in Japan. The "Fujiyama" roller coaster in Japan is a Guinness book of world records holder for being  the largest rolled coaster in the world. The first plunge is 70 meters high at a 65 degree angle and reaches a speed of 145 km/h at the bottom... Not sure if it still holds the record or not...  At the same park they have another Guinness book of world records holder called "Dodompa". Not sure about the spelling... It holds the record for the fastest roller coaster in the world. I don't know what the top speed is though. It was closed for maintenace for most of the day when I was there. I got to see it running though and it was pretty fast....  Both coasters have huge Guinness plaques next to their respective entrances... So I think the records are legit.  The park is close to Mt. Fuji so it also has a pretty amazing view.

That was FUNNY! But I remember being on the Texas Cyclone at Six Flags Houston,Tx. We were in the first seat, and all was good until.....We got to the crest of the 1st drop, sat there for like 15 minutes, then the damn thing rolled BACKWARDS all the way back through the boarding area. We stopped (Wish I was kidding!!!!) for like a nano second, and they didn't even check on us, they just shipped up through again! Luckily all was good the 2nd time, but I stayed away from that ride for a WHILE after that. And this was Â way before you started to really hear about carnival, and theme park ride accidents, and mechanical failures. In fact the very last roller coaster I rode was the Silver Bullet out on Kemah Boardwalk,Tx. My Husband and I foolishly chose to ride together. Problem w/that? I had not lost my 80 lbs yet, and we both had on thick coats for the weather. This is an ALL wood coaster. At the time I believe I was 30....Something, and after the ride from HELL way through, we both said NO MORE! So IF we ever ride another one, it's gonna be steel baby! You FEEL everything on a wooden coaster, and it is NOT for people w/existing major injuries, or are easily injured. But if you're young, and crazy...Or old and crazy, give em both a shot. But for me and my Man, it's nothing but steel coasters for us!

"We're here at the Universal Orlando resort, home of the greatest roller coasters in the world." Um, no, Universal Orlando is not the home of the greatest coasters in the world. Yes, they do have a couple of really good coasters. And yes, Hulk is still one of my favorites, but UEO is not the home of the greatest coasters in the world. Not when Cedar Point, Six Flags Magic Mountain, and Six Flags Great Adventure have larger collections and coasters that are actual Top 10. In fact, most years since 2000, No 1 and No 2 in the world have alternated between Millennium Force at Cedar Point and Bizarro (aka Superman Ride of Steel) at Six Flags New England). Busch Gardens in Tampa actually has a better collection of coasters and most rate higher than Universal's Orlando coasters. But at least Universal has better coasters than the 4 Walt Disney World parks (in total, seven coasters in three parks). But what do I know, I mean other than the fact that I've ridden 220 coasters.

Â I'm making this comment because, in this world of ours everything has to be bigger and faster, more exciting, but sometimes the G-force is too much for some of us hence I stick to the older coasters - granted I really don't want to go on them anymore, and the randomness of this happening to Aviva is just that, but you never know.

Cedar Point has won the Golden Ticket Award from Amusement Today for "Best Amusement Park in the World" for 16 consecutive years.[9] The park has also placed in categories for "Friendliest Park Staff" (2002, 2004 - 2006), "Cleanest Park" (2004, 2005), "Best Capacity" (1998 - 2002), "Best Kid's Area" (2004, 2013), "Best Outdoor Night Production" (2004 - 2007), "Best Shows" (2004, 2005), "Best Games Area" (2002), "Best Souvenirs" (2002), and "Best Halloween Event" (2005 - 2008, 2013). The park also won the Golden Ticket Award for "Best New Ride of 2007" with the roller coaster Maverick.[76] Cedar Point has also won several IAAPA awards, including the Applause Award in 1996.[77]  Cedar Point's roller coasters are commonly ranked high in the Golden Ticket Awards. In the 2013 rankings, GateKeeper debuted at 28th, making it the first time ever that the park has six steel roller coasters in the top 50. The following steel and wooden coasters were ranked by Amusement Today in 2013:[9]  Steel[edit]  Millennium Force: 1st Magnum XL-200: 9th Top Thrill Dragster: 12th Maverick: 22nd GateKeeper: 28th Raptor: 30th  Wood[edit]  Blue Streak: 27th  'Nuff said.
